				\begin{document}$$ N\mathrm{D}=\left(2/e\varepsilon {\varepsilon}_0\right){\left[\frac{d{C}^{-2}}{dE}\right]}^{-1} $$\end{document}when the following values are taken into account: e = 1.6 × 10−19, ε0 = 8.86 × 10−14 F/cm, and ε = 31 for anatase [56]. The calculated donor densities of TiO2 NTs and B-TiO2 NTs equal to 1.98 × 1020 and 1.82 × 1021 cm−3, respectively. Despite the fact that the Mott-Schottky plot does not allow to estimate the absolute value of ND [57], it is shown that upon electrochemical doping, donor density is ten times higher comparing to the unmodified sample. Such change was observed for other modified titania samples and is commonly attributed to the introduction of substantial oxygen vacancies that are regarded as electron donors in titania [58, 59] and implied faster carrier transfer in doped TiO2 comparing to pure titania [60].
